{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522855"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:49:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13852"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13852","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13852"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.59,0.04,0.33,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88376"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6469"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13852"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72571"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"5569"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12804"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30132"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43446"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"88376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/88376"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine health check. He has no significant medical history. He drinks 60 units of alcohol per week and has a 30 pack-year smoking history. He takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears cachectic. His vital signs are within normal limits. Digital examination reveals increased nail bed angle and sponginess, with loss of the normal angle between the nail plate and proximal nail fold (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying cause of his finger clubbing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inflammatory bowel disease","Bronchogenic carcinoma","Cystic fibrosis","Chronic liver disease","Bacterial endocarditis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with digital clubbing in the context of significant smoking history. \u003Cstrong\u003EBronchogenic carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely underlying cause given his significant 30 pack-year smoking history and cachectic appearance. The combination of heavy smoking, alcohol use, and unexplained clubbing should raise suspicion for underlying malignancy, particularly lung cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic liver disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause clubbing, particularly in the setting of alcoholic cirrhosis. While this patient has a significant alcohol history (60 units per week), there are no other clinical features of chronic liver disease mentioned, making this less likely than bronchogenic carcinoma in a heavy smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E can be associated with clubbing, particularly in ulcerative colitis. However, there are no symptoms suggestive of inflammatory bowel disease in this case, such as diarrhoea, abdominal pain, or weight loss specifically attributed to bowel symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial endocarditis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with clubbing, but it typically presents with other features such as fever, heart murmurs, and systemic symptoms. The absence of these features makes acute endocarditis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECystic fibrosis\u003C/strong\u003E commonly causes clubbing, but it is typically diagnosed in childhood and would be extremely unusual to present for the first time at age 45. Additionally, the patient would likely have had a history of recurrent respiratory infections and other manifestations of cystic fibrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClubbing is a paraneoplastic phenomenon that occurs in approximately 30% of patients with bronchogenic carcinoma. The exact mechanism is not fully understood but is thought to involve platelet-derived growth factor and vascular endothelial growth factor. The presence of unexplained clubbing should always prompt investigation for underlying malignancy, particularly in patients with risk factors such as smoking.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Digital clubbing is associated with various conditions including bronchogenic carcinoma, inflammatory bowel disease, and chronic liver disease.","Clubbing is characterised by increased nail bed angle, sponginess of nail bed, and loss of the normal angle between nail plate and proximal nail fold.","The presence of clubbing should prompt investigation for underlying cardiopulmonary, gastrointestinal, or malignant disease."],"references":["Burcovschii S, Aboeed A. Nail Clubbing [Internet]. PubMed. StatPearls Publishing; 2021. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539713/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72571"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13852"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20799"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20799"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/S0iR40IqUzctcV4WqP94kJKh79XOtz.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/S0iR40IqUzctcV4WqP94kJKh79XOtz.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"72571","links":{"self":"ht